## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. The replacement uses cooperative cancellation with `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### If you cannot modify the `Func<T>` signature (uncooperative work)

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        if (task.Wait(timeout))
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }

        // Work continues on the thread pool — it cannot be forcibly stopped
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

> ⚠️ This version **abandons** the work but cannot kill it. The thread pool thread continues running until `work` completes naturally.

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` must be called inside loops/between steps in `work`. Without checkpoints, the timeout won't interrupt CPU-bound work. |
| **Blocking calls ignore the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, synchronous I/O won't respond. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O instead. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **No true "kill" in managed .NET** | If you truly need to terminate uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |

---

### Caller migration example

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeExpensiveResult(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// After (.NET 8) — work must cooperate
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return FinalResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

The first (cooperative) version is strongly preferred—it guarantees the work actually stops on timeout.
